value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + D-mannose = ADP + D-mannose 6-phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: beta-nicotinamide D-ribonucleotide + H2O = beta-nicotinate D-ribonucleotide + NH3.
Catalysis of the reaction: H2O + nicotinamide mononucleotide = D-ribose 5-phosphate + H+ + nicotinamide.
Catalysis of the reaction: an alpha,omega-diamine + 2-oxoglutarate = an omega-aminoaldehyde + L-glutamate.
Catalysis of the reaction: oxaloacetate + pyridoxamine = L-aspartate + pyridoxal.
Catalysis of the reaction: pyridoxamine 5'-phosphate + 2-oxoglutarate = pyridoxal 5'-phosphate + D-glutamate.
Catalysis of the reaction: pyruvate + CoA + 2 oxidized ferredoxin = acetyl-CoA + CO2 + 2 reduced ferredoxin + 2 H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + thiamine = ADP + 2 H+ + thiamine phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: acyl-CoA + NADP+ = trans-2,3-dehydroacyl-CoA + NADPH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: 2-octaprenylphenol + NADPH + O2 + H+ = 2-octaprenyl-6-hydroxyphenol + NADP+ + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: (R)-lactaldehyde + NAD+ = methylglyoxal + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: a (3R)-hydroxyacyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] = a (2E)-enoyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: methylglyoxal + H2O = D-lactate.

definition.value: Note that this term was reinstated from obsolete. Also note that this enzymatic activity converts methylglyoxal to D-lactate in a single glutathione (GSH)-independent step. The other known route for this conversion is the two-step GSH-dependent pathway catalyzed by EC:4.4.1.5 (lactoylglutathione lyase) and EC:3.1.2.6 (hydroxyacylglutathione hydrolase).

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: tetrahydrothiophene 1-oxide + reduced acceptor = tetrahydrothiophene + acceptor.
Catalysis of the reaction: dihydroneopterin monophosphate = dihydroneopterin + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: dihydroneopterin triphosphate = dihydroneopterin phosphate + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: H2O + NADP+ = NAD+ + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: dTDP-4-amino-4,6-dideoxy-D-glucose + 2-oxoglutarate = dTDP-4-dehydro-6-deoxy-D-glucose + L-glutamate.
Catalysis of the reaction: 2-oxoglutarate + dTDP-4-amino-4,6-dideoxy-D-galactose = L-glutamate + dTDP-4-dehydro-6-deoxy-D-galactose.
Catalysis of the reaction: a halohydrin = an epoxide + a hydrogen halide.
Enables the energy-independent facilitated diffusion of a chloride ion through a transmembrane channel that opens when bound to histamine.
A protein complex that forms a transmembrane channel through which chloride ions may pass in response to histamine binding to the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.
The biosynthetic process in which peptide bond formation occurs in the absence of the translational machinery. Examples include the synthesis of antibiotic peptides, and glutathione.
A protein complex that recognizes the proximal sequence element of RNA polymerase II and III snRNA promoters.
Catalysis of the transfer of an acyl group from acyl-CoA to a nitrogen atom on an acceptor molecule.
Catalysis of the transfer of a mannose residue to an oligosaccharide, forming a beta-(1->4) linkage.

Enables the transfer of cellobiose from one side of a membrane to the other. Cellobiose, or 4-O-beta-D-glucopyranosyl-D-glucose, is a disaccharide that represents the basic repeating unit of cellulose.

Enables the transfer of sorbose from one side of a membrane to the other. Sorbose is the ketohexose xylo-2-hexulose; L-sorbose is formed by bacterial oxidation of sorbitol. Sorbose is produced commercially by fermentation and is used as an intermediate in the manufacture of ascorbic acid.

Enables the transfer of galactosamine from one side of a membrane to the other. Galactosamine is an aminodeoxysugar; D-galactosamine is a constituent of some glycolipids and glycosaminoglycans, commonly as its N-acetyl derivative.
Includes phosphoenolpyruvate-protein phosphatase (enzyme I of the phosphotransferase system) and protein-N(PI)-phosphohistidine-sugar phosphotransferase (enzyme II of the phosphotransferase system).

Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction: a phosphoprotein + H2O = a protein + phosphate.

Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction: a protein + ATP = a phosphoprotein + ADP.
Catalysis of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to a carbohydrate substrate molecule.
Catalysis of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to an amino acid substrate.
Catalysis of the reaction: carbohydrate phosphate + H2O = carbohydrate + phosphate.
Catalysis of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP or GTP, to a nucleobase, nucleoside, nucleotide or polynucleotide substrate.
Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + nucleoside = ADP + nucleoside monophosphate.
Modulates the activity of a kinase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to a substrate molecule.
Binds to and modulates the activity of a phosphatase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the removal of a phosphate group from a substrate molecule.
Binds to and increases the activity of a kinase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to a substrate molecule.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a kinase.
Binds to and increases the activity of a phosphatase.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a phosphatase.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of an acetyl group or groups from a substrate molecule.

Binding to an intermediate filament, a distinct elongated structure, characteristically 10 nm in diameter, that occurs in the cytoplasm of higher eukaryotic cells. Intermediate filaments form a fibrous system, composed of chemically heterogeneous subunits and involved in mechanically integrating the various components of the cytoplasmic space.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving lipids.

label.value: regulation of fatty acid metabolic process

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving fatty acids.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving steroids.

label.value: regulation of nucleobase-containing compound metabolic process

value.value: Any cellular process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving phosphates.
